<font color="#FF0000">PACIFISM</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 30  6:23:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
SW &amp; John,<br><br>
I will write the title down in my notebook, and may run across the book sometime. Our library has limited shelf space, but is able to order stuff.<br><br>
The pacifists that I met in Vietnam made a good impression on me. One was a combat medic who served with me in C company 1/52. He actually came over as a rifleman before I got there, and for some reason, our company commander allowed him to be a medic. I have no recollection as to whether he had received medical training as a civilian, but I know that he had a combat MOS - 11b. He was medivacced from our company after being badly wounded in a firefight.<br><br>
He earned the trust of his comrades, as happens to all good medics who risk their lives in order to come to the aid of others.<br><br>
Aiding others is what the American Friends did in Quang Ngai City. My final 3 months in Vietnam were spent working with another CO medic who had served with a different rifle company (maybe Delta). Medcaps that I participated in, and helped organize, were my most rewarding duties as a soldier.<br><br>
My first 8 months in country made me aware of the agony of the Vietnamese people. I admired the American Friends because they *took it upon themselves* to do something about it. As far as I know, no one even had to ask them, let alone draft them.<br><br>
Some people didn't see fit to answer the call. But there were those who answered the call from God. Many times I have sat in church congregations and heard them profess they were not of *this* world, but of God's world.<br><br>
None of us are free of hypocrisy. It is a common human weakness. Yet, I oftentimes have thought how the American Friends in Vietnam demonstrated their faith in a positive and courageous manner.<br><br>

